                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shareable summary:</strong> Copy a clean text summary
                  of all local times to paste into emails or chat.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Business‑hour overlay:</strong> Quickly spot fair
                  meeting times for global teams.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Behind the scenes: how time zone conversion works</h2>
              <p>
                Modern operating systems maintain a database of time zones (the
                IANA tz database). Each time zone includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  A base offset from UTC (for example, UTC−5 hours for Eastern
                  Standard Time).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rules for daylight saving time (start and end dates, offset
                  changes).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                When you select a date, time, and time zone, the browser
                converts that local time to a precise UTC timestamp. From there,
                it can compute the corresponding local time in any other time
                zone.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Conceptual formula</p>
                <p>
                  1. Convert local time in Zone A to UTC:<br />
                  <code
                    >UTC = LocalTime<sub>A</sub> −
                    Offset<sub>A</sub>(date)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  2. Convert UTC to local time in Zone B:<br />
                  <code
                    >LocalTime<sub>B</sub> = UTC +
                    Offset<sub>B</sub>(date)</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-gray-600">
                  The offsets Offset<sub>A</sub> and Offset<sub>B</sub> depend
                  on the date because of daylight saving time.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Common pitfalls when working across time zones</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ignoring daylight saving time:</strong> Offsets can
                  change by one hour on specific dates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Assuming fixed offsets for countries:</strong> Some
                  countries have multiple time zones (e.g., USA, Canada, Russia,
                  Australia).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Using ambiguous abbreviations:</strong> “CST” can mean
                  Central Standard Time (North America), China Standard Time, or
                  Cuba Standard Time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Crossing the International Date Line:</strong> The
                  local date can be different by a full day in another region.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for scheduling global meetings</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Include the time in <strong>UTC</strong> in your invites
                  (e.g., “15:00 UTC”).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use this calculator to check that no one is outside reasonable
                  local hours.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Avoid days when some regions switch DST (late March, early
                  April, late October, early November).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rotate meeting times if your team spans very distant time
                  zones.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Does this time zone calculator work offline?</h3>
              <p>
                The logic runs entirely in your browser, but it relies on your
                device’s time zone database. It will usually keep working
                offline once loaded, but you should refresh occasionally to pick
                up any updated DST rules.
              </p>

              <h3>Why do I see different offsets on different dates?</h3>
              <p>
                Many regions move clocks forward in spring and back in autumn.
                The offset from UTC therefore depends on the date. This tool
                automatically applies the correct offset for each date you
                choose.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my city is not listed?</h3>
              <p>
                Choose another city in the same time zone, or select the generic
                time zone entry (for example, “UTC+08:00”) if available. The
                actual time will be the same for all locations in that zone.
              </p>
